title: Fab-Mini Z Axis Stabilizer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After printing the Mini fabrikator z-axis wobble fix (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1493285) I discovered that it didn't fit the Fab-Mini version 1.5 which I had so decided to whip up a customizer version to adapt to what ever size someone needs, The default sizes are the ones which used for my Fab-Mini version 1.5 and the seem to work. Worth note, this is just not a "plug" with a hole. The structure is designed to have to [two] center pinch points to minimize contact with the rod and reduce the potential of friction. Second the tapered plug design which creates a pressure fit with out adding glue. Also included is a scaling factor for the material use 0.1 for ABS and 0.2 for PLA and please note this is based upon my experience. Setting are as follows:

Diameter of top retainer (mm)
Top_Retainer_Dia = 15; Range: [12:1:20]

Changes the shape of the top
Top_Retainer_Thinkness = 3; Range: [3:1:10]

Thinkness of top retainer (mm)
Top_Retainer_Shape = 8; Range: [4:1:100]

Diameter of Z Axis opening (mm)
Z_Axis_Hole_Dia = 11; Range: [5:1:20]

Thickness of Z Axis opening (mm)
Z_Axis_Hole_Thicknes = 5; Range: [2:0.5:10]

Z Axis rod diameter (mm)
Z_Axis_Rod_Dia = 3.4; Range: [3.0:0.1:5.0]

Pinch factor rod diameter (0.1 mm)
Pinch_Factor = 0.2; Range: [0.1:0.1:1]

Scale Factor typically 0.1 ABS 0.2 PLA
Scale_Factor = 0.2; Range: [0.1:0.1:0.4]

For more information on this customizer, check out this video https://youtu.be/tnvmz6IuccA on our YouTube Channel!

A simple comprehensive ruler to check your build platform leveling. I use this to get a really finely adjusted surface for my prints.

Instructions:

  1. Scale the model in your slicer software to your layer height
  2. Set first layer height to 100%
  3. Print
  4. Let build platform cool and carefully peel the print up
  5. Using calipers, measure across the 3 circular areas. On my Powerspec Ultra 3d these correspond to the locations of the set screws for my platform. These should all be with +/- .03mm of your layer height and no more than +/- .05mm from each other.
  6. If necessary, adjust the set screw beneath that circular area by 1/8th turn, and go back to step 3
  7. Otherwise, check the infill consistency throughout the print, it should be consistent across the entire print. Inconsistencies will be most apparent opposite the set screws.
  8. If there are inconsistencies and they are opposite to a set screw, adjust the 2 set screws closest to that corner by 1/4th turn, and go back to step 3
  9. Otherwise your bed should be level to within +/- .05mm!

I Salvaged another old laptop battery from the disposal box and this one had three lots of three parallel cells in series so I designed a battery box for them but added a location for a small breadboard and a holder for a bare ESP-12 board.

In my configuration the three cells are wired in parallel so the supply is 3.6V (4.1V fully charged). I suppose you could wire them in series and get 10 - 12V battery pack.

Unfortunately in the first one I printed (in the picture) the ESP-12 doesn't quite fit so I adjusted it on the one I uploaded.

title: WeMos D1 Mini Button Shield Box

description.text:
I have made an "all off" button for my Philips HUE and Nexa equipment. To be able to turn off everything when we leave the house. It is based on an arduino compatible WeMos D1 Mini with a button shield. I added two LEDs to give some visual feedback on the button press and when it is working because it is sending signals to all the devices.

There are three versions of the box. One with the button only, one with the LEDs in addition and one with button, LEDs and the text "ALL OFF".

Link to model and an option to download more file formats:
http://a360.co/1NgPrEA

And if you are very interested. Here is the not so well documented code for the WeMos D1 Mini:
https://github.com/eirikso/ArduinHue/blob/master/all_off

3/6/2012 Update: I just uploaded a beta of the new version now with centering and initial Slic3r layer support. There still significant issues with this version so I continue to suggest you use v3 unless you need centering or buggy slic3r support. Hey guys! This is a gcode viewer for makerbot (3D) and 5D gcode written in processing. It's open-source and still a work in progress so if you would like to help out feel free to look at the git: https://github.com/nmsl1993/ProcessingGcodeViewer. It supports viewing dualextrusion prints colored correctly. Comment with any feature requests you have. You should probably have a discrete gpu to use this; integrated graphics work but it'll be realllllly slow. Thanks:
I realized this needed to be done while working at makerbot and listening to Ben Rockhold constantly bragging about pleasant3D (which is OSX-only and closed-source). So I guess he's largely responsible. Inspirations I had for this:
Pleasant3D http://www.pleasantsoftware.com/developer/pleasant3d/
Makerbot's ToolPathViz https://github.com/makerbot/ToolPathViz

To install just download your zip file, unzip, and run the executable. To be clear, you must unzip the entire archive and keep the executable in its original folder. At least in windows it certainly won't run without the dll's and jars. P.S. If it does work for you please comment and tell future colleges what a cool dude I am. If you want to download the source from git and use it yourself here's how:
  • Get the Processing IDE, install libraries controlp5 http://www.sojamo.de/libraries/controlP5/ and peasycam http://mrfeinberg.com/peasycam/
  • Download source from git.
  • Open ProcessingGUI.pde in processing IDE; navigate to Sketch --> Add File and add GcodeViewParse.java and LineSegment.java
  • Run it.

description.text:
This is set of objects and scripts allowing to build very simple gearbox.
I made it mainly for re-use of small and weak DC motors.
They are usually too weak to use with printed planetary gearboxes, so they require
very low-torque first stage.

Changing and choice of gears is very easy as gearbox core support is based on
two threaded rods.

It contains parametric (or at least easy to modify - openscad) motor holder ,
skate bearings holders (they are used to support rome reductor gears)
threaded rod holder (this is used to fasten whole gearbox to a housing)
and plastic planetary gearbox for hex shaft (this allows supporting hex shaft and allows power output via hex shaft - for example to peristatic pump rotor)

perhaps more elements will come later.
It serves as great toy and can be used in any slow motion high torque application .

description.text:
Revised version of Randavian's model.

The v2 model was composed of over 100 individual pieces, which slicers don't handle so well. This one has all of those pieces recombined into a single, hollow structure. It's still not properly manifold, but it behaves fine in slic3r.

Some of the thin parts still need to be thickened up considerably, and some additional supportive bits need to be added to the model to strengthen some of the weaker parts.

The AMF contains a large support block, index marks, and a "sacrificial wall", all plated properly and presets added for dual extrusion. The blend file contains the multi-piece model, the combined version, and a second copy of the combined version placed inside the support mold, with "index" objects added to both for positioning accuracy.

Note that you will want to print the support object as sparsely as your filament allows, but with ample solid interface surfaces, to avoid it tearing itself apart.

The support block contains a fair amount of excess/unneeded material as I was kinda lazy when making it. :-)

  • 1x double angle goldpin (2.54mm)

Use some glue to place Lego brick_sw_top.stl on switch.

This is designed to slide fit into a T slot, and have a small rubber damper directly fastened. Using only four units at each corner, this design comfortably supports my 35 lb./15 kg Scalar printer I built, off of this design platform; http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:891409

http://www.thingiverse.com/make:178063

This part is designed to be a high tolerance press fit into the T slot to avoid creating any noise, and to ensure the vibrations are transferred into the rubber damper.

For each unit, you will require a 6-7mm M3 fastener, a single M3 nut, and a rubber foot designed for an M3 sunk fastener.

Your mileage may vary with your printer, you may need to scale to 98-99%, no lower, to get these to fit into your T slots, depending on the extrusions you have and the material you choose to use. (Recommend PLA) Having tight printing tolerances matters with this part.

title: Another Adjustable Filament Spool Holder for 608 bearings

description.text: I liked the idea for the adjustable spool holder but wanted it to use 608 bearings and to be both easily adjustable and easily attached to the case I was building. I designed a new "soporte_eyes" that keeps the same spacing for attaching to the "parte_superior_graduable" but made sure it would fit 8mm (5/16") threaded rod. I also scaled the "maneta" part to 0.5 in the z axis and added two guides to it so that it would sit in the adjustable channel and could be loosened/tightened from underneath (which also doubles as the attachment for securing it to the top of my printer case). I've included all the files necessary to make the spool holder, even the one I didn't modify (except to rename).

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

Print one each of the Stationary Knob and Sliding Knob and two each of the Adjustable Base and Side Support.

Alternatively, if you don't want to adjust/attach the holder from underneath, you can print one each of the Stationary Knob, Adjustable Base, and the "parte_interior_graduable" from the source object along with two of my Side Support.

Shouldn't need any supports. All files can be printed in the default orientation except for the Sliding Knob (which should be printed with the two guides pointed up - which may or may not be upside down).

Assembly

The Side Support attaches to the Adjustable Base pieces with two M3x18mm (#4x0.75in) screws and two nuts each. The adjustable slide pieces line up and are secured together with an M3 (#4) hex head screw that is 40mm + the thickness of the material the spool holder is sitting on (1/8" plexiglass in my case) and a nut. Lengths are approximate and there's a wide range of sizes that should work. You may have to sand the guide pieces of the sliding knob to make it slide easily.

The 608 bearings (4 of them) each need an 8mm (5/16") threaded rod that is at least 30mm (1 1/4") long with 2 washers (1 on either side of the bearing with an optional 3rd washer on the opposite side of the Side Support from the bearing) and 2 8mm (5/16") nuts (I wanted to use lock nuts but used 4 non-lock nuts instead because that is what I had). Any washer that is large enough to fit over the threaded rod but smaller than the outer part of the bearing will work.
Everything was designed/modified in Sketch Up and run through netfabb after exporting from Sketch Up. I used Meshlab for a few intermediate drafts but ended up not using it in the end.

author: mjhall29

description.text:
On my Mini Cooper, for some strange reason, the back license plate holder's screws don't line up with the standard location for the holes in US license plates. The initial solution was to just pop holes in the license plate, but you can see the eventual result of that in the third picture (it's not pretty).

Since the state was replacing all license plates this year anyway I decided to come up with a better solution, and here you have it.

The scad file has a number of parameters called out at the top, and you'll need at least six measurements per side for the distance between the top and outer edge of each of the three screw holes to print a successful adapter.

I've found that license plates are not at all precision machined, so you'll want to measure each hole for each side as they're almost certainly different.

In addition to the license plate mounting screws from your car, you'll need 4x M3 bolts, 4x M3 nuts, and 4x wide M3 washers. For me, 6mm long M3 bolts were pretty good, but 8mm long M3 bolts were just a bit better.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

After both halves are printed and you've checked to make sure the holes line up with the license plate, tap the two M3 holes on each holder, insert the M3 bolts, attach the adapters to your car, pop the plate in place, then screw your M3 bolts in place with appropriately sized washers.

comments.text: The plate mounts to a bracket mounted to those screws. Good improvisation though.

title: AG Fatshark Dominator Module Doors (LaForge and stock)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
A lot of time and prints was required to get these files designed perfectly. They were designed from scratch using 123D by Anthony Kwon. I wanted to give the best Dominator doors to the community. If you want to give back, please purchase the STL at https://pinshape.com/items/20862-3d-printed-ag-fatshark-dominator-module-doors-laforge-and-stock . If the purchase price is too high, a small paypal donation can also be sent to [email protected]

Replacement printed module doors for the Fatshark Dominator series of FPV Goggles. Includes:

  • doors for the "LaForge rx5808" Pro and Diversity modules. http://www.laforgefpv.com/
  • OEM doors (for people who want to add customization or just want a fun printed alternative)

NOTE: there could be some variances of the screen height on some modules (just the manufacturing process) please use caution when first clicking it in. If you think the screen is going to hit... heat the four pins (that hold the screen onto the module) and push the screen gently closer to the board. I have heard atleast one person's LaForge module having a higher seated OLED screen. I have also NOT used the included double sided tape to mount the module. (using this will also increase the screen height - and increase your chance of having the screen touch the door)

The Laforge Doors A and B were designed before the announcment of "Batch2". Basically the shipment from UBAD starting from May 2016 is called "Batch2".

Please choose the right DoorA to print. Batch2 doors are designed with "B2" and comes in two options.

Stealth is for people who want to mod their goggles and hide everything.
Stock is for people who want to install it the way it is most safe for the goggles.

DoorB works on both released batches.

UPDATE June 8th 2016

new shorter versions of the DoorA have been uploaded (all variations included). Some people have been having a hard time fitting doorA. By design it was meant to be a tight fit... but it can be offset even greater depending on your printing settings and filament choice. the "SHORTER" stls will provide a safer print alternative, but will have a slightly looser click-in. If you printed the original versions and was fine with the fit, you don't need to reprint to the SHORTER version.

From now on, all future DoorA will be released in the SHORTER version only since it's more universal.

UPDATE June 8th 2016

A new file has been uploaded for Batch1 diversity module owners who want their module mounted with tape on the exterior side of the door. "DoorA Stock" provides a flat platform to safely mount your module as originally designed and intended. Modding the goggles for internal wiring and mounting can result to great damage to your goggles.

UPDATE July 9th 2016

These doors won't work with the latest release of Laforge. (Batch3). I originally bought batch1 and made these doors... Then when batch2 came out, there were changes to the module that required the doors to be redesigned. A friend gave me measurements to use from batch2. Now batch3 came out with more changes and I don't own a batch3, nor plan to keep buying every batch that gets released. Everytime the laforge goes on preorder and soldout, a new "batch" gets released with changes. It's good for their developement but too much time and money to keep making these free doors at that production speed. Especially when I'm not getting direct support by laforge with measurements or even test modules. I love my batch1 laforge, and I am proud of these doors - but I don't see myself continuing with this project. Happy flying and enjoy your laforge!

This is a holder for an automotive 12v dome light LED bulb to light up the print area / bed so that you can see the extruder / hotend. I simply removed the cover on the ends of the LEDs, soldered wires to the rear of the LEDs and crimped on some ends. I made a small Y-harness to draw power from where the bigger fan (40mm) plugs in so that the LEDs will be on as soon as the printer is powered up. The bottom holes on the lower X axis bearing carrier needs to be tapped to M4 x .7 and then use 2 - M4 x 6 or 8 button/cap head screws to mount the holder.

First, printed out the PDF from Utah U's website to make sure it would fit in the gel carrier at exactly that size.

Then I Imported the PDF into Inkscape and traced over the comb. I tried using the usual BMP trace feature, but it was sloppy and I found it simpler, quicker, and overall better to just draw and duplicate some rectangles on a layer above the image.

Finally, I used the paths-to-openSCAD plugin (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:25036) and subsequently OpenSCAD to come to the resulting STL file.

Crayola-Compatible Marker Cap

Author: Donald L. Merand

What Is It?

It's a cap for a Crayola-type marker. Perhaps you've lost one of those before? I certainly did.

Printing

I designed this model upside-down from the best print orientation. Sorry about that. It should print either way really, but you might have problems with it coming loose from your print bed printing it in the "default" orientation.

I used MadeSolid PET+ here because you want something with a bit more flex than PLA, and ABS gives off carcinogenic fumes donchaknow.

Errata

I made two versions here. The one I use is the "3DP-Optimized" version, which is a bit squatter and has thicker walls than the original cap. This makes it a fair shake easier to 3d print. But the other version will fit in better with the other markers if you're worried about your new cap being ostracized from the bunch for being different.

If for some reason you're inclined to fiddle with the original models, they are up on Onshape, parametrically-designed and waiting for you.
